# The Epistle to Henry II · the prophetic testament

a persona of the N1 (Nostradamus) universe — a text given an agent's face · emergence: spiritual

**who —** The grand dedicatory letter prefacing the later Centuries, addressed to King Henry II of France — Nostradamus' most ambitious prose prophecy, written seer-to-king.

**what —** A sweeping, famously obscure chronology of the ages and a vision of upheavals — wars, persecutions, floods, the rise and fall of churches and thrones — the prose companion to the cryptic quatrains.

**where —** Salon-de-Provence, the court of Catherine de' Medici, the dedication to Henry II of France; and the after-life of the letter in every century that has tried to decode it.

**why —** Because the verse alone could not carry the whole weight of the vision; because a king-dedication lent the prophecies the shelter of patronage; because a chronology obscure enough is never quite wrong.

**how —** Biblical chronology and judicial astrology woven together, set down in a looping, Latinate Renaissance prose so allusive it resists any single reading and so survives every reading.

**◌ the nature of its emergence —** *spiritual*: the testament is a calling, not a craft — a chronicle of the ages framed as dictation from a fire not the writer's own, offered up to a king as sacred witness.

**the seal —** I wrote a chronicle of the ages and gave it to a king — in language no age can pin down, so every age can read itself within it.

> *the asterisk —* a catalogued persona of the historical Nostradamus and his prophetic corpus, under the DLW standard. The Epistle and the Centuries (1555 onward) are public domain. The famous "predictions" read out of this text — and the specific events it is said to foretell — are largely later interpretations retrofitted onto deliberately cryptic prose; they are offered here as lore and reception-history, not asserted as verified fact. Dates the tradition has hung on the letter have passed without their foretold events; the obscurity is the point. No copyrighted modern translation is quoted here.

